      {
        "segment": "Recap & Hook",
        "minutes": 5,
        "purpose": "Refresh hydrocarbon naming and introduce the -OH functional group context."
      },
      {
        "segment": "Core Concept: Alcohols vs Phenols",
        "minutes": 10,
        "purpose": "Define structures and establish the fundamental difference (sp3 vs sp2/aromatic)."
      },
      {
        "segment": "Nomenclature & Classification",
        "minutes": 15,
        "purpose": "Teach IUPAC rules for naming and classify alcohols into primary/secondary/tertiary."
      },
      {
        "segment": "Guided Practice & Q&A",
        "minutes": 10,
        "purpose": "Apply concepts to structures and address misconceptions."
      },
      {
        "segment": "Summary & Bridge",
        "minutes": 5,
        "purpose": "Recap key definitions and preview the next session (Physical Properties)."
      }
    ],
    "sessionSummary": [
      "Alcohols have -OH on sp3 carbon; Phenols have it on an aromatic ring.",
      "IUPAC naming prioritizes the longest chain containing OH, ending in '-ol'.",
      "Classification (1°, 2°, 3°) depends on how many carbons are attached to the C-OH."
    ],
    "nextSessionBridge": [
      "Now that we know what they look like and how to name them, next class we will explore why alcohols have higher boiling points than hydrocarbons (Physical Properties)."
    ]
  },
  "studentLessonNotes": {
    "title": "Alcohols & Phenols: Introduction",
    "introduction": "Welcome to the world of Oxygenated Hydrocarbons! You already know about alkanes and alkenes. Today, we meet a new functional group that changes everything: The Hydroxyl Group (-OH). But wait—is every compound with an -OH group called 'alcohol'? Not quite!",
    "learningObjectives": [
      "Distinguish between Alcohols and Phenols based on structure.",
      "Apply IUPAC rules to name mono-hydric alcohols and phenols.",
      "Classify alcohols as primary, secondary, or tertiary."
    ],
    "quickRecall": [
      "What is a functional group?",
      "How do you number the longest carbon chain in an alkane?"
    ],
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Alcohols vs. Phenols: The Big Difference",
        "explanation": "Both contain -OH, but their environment is different.",
        "keyPoints": [
          "Alcohol (R-OH): -OH attached to an aliphatic carbon chain (sp3 hybridized). Example: Ethanol.",
          "Phenol (Ar-OH): -OH directly attached to a benzene ring (aromatic/aryl group).",
          "They are NOT the same class of compounds."
        ],
        "examples": [
          "Ethanol (CH3-CH2-OH) is an alcohol.",
          "Phenol (C6H5-OH) is a phenol, not 'phenyl alcohol' in IUPAC naming."
        ],
        "whyItMatters": "This structural difference causes Phenols to be more acidic and behave differently in reactions compared to alcohols later.",
        "terminology": [
          "Alkyl group",
          "Aryl ring"
        ],
        "detailedExplanation": "In Alcohols, the carbon holding the oxygen is saturated (single bonds only). In Phenols, that carbon is part of a double-bonded aromatic system. This makes them chemically distinct.",
        "observedIn": [
          "Solubility in water",
          "Reaction with bases"
        ],
        "visualSupport": [
          "Diagram: Ethanol (chain) vs Phenol (ring)"
        ],
        "importantNotes": [
          "Never call phenol 'phenyl alcohol' in IUPAC names."
        ],
        "memoryTechniques": [
          "'Phenol has a Ring, Alcohol is a Chain.'"
        ],
        "conceptSummary": [
          "Alcohol = Alkane + OH; Phenol = Benzene + OH (directly)."
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "IUPAC Nomenclature",
        "explanation": "How to name these compounds systematically.",
        "keyPoints": [
          "Select the longest carbon chain containing the -OH group.",
          "Number from the end nearest to the -OH group (lowest number).",
          "Replace '-e' of alkane with '-ol'.",
          "For Phenols, 'benzene' becomes 'phenol'; OH is at position 1 by default."
        ],
        "examples": [
          "CH3-CH2-OH -> Ethanol (not ethyl alcohol in IUPAC).",
          "C6H5-OH -> Phenol.",
          "(CH3)2CH-OH -> Propan-2-ol"
        ],
        "whyItMatters": [
          "Standard naming allows chemists worldwide to know exactly which molecule you mean."
        ],
        "terminology": [
          "Parent chain",
          "Suffix -ol"
        ],
        "detailedExplanation": "If there are multiple OH groups, use di-, tri- (e.g., ethane-1,2-diol). For phenols with substituents, number the ring starting from C-OH as 1.",
        "observedIn": [
          "Chemical labels",
          "Reaction equations"
        ],
        "visualSupport": [
          "Numbering arrows on a chain."
        ],
        "importantNotes": [
          "The carbon with OH gets the lowest possible number, even if it means higher numbers for other groups (unless priority rules differ in later chapters)."
        ],
        "memoryTechniques": [
          "'Lowest Number Rule' - Count from the side closest to the party!"
        ],
        "conceptSummary": [
          "Longest chain + OH position = Name."
        ]
      },
      {
        "heading": "Classification of Alcohols",
        "explanation": "Not all alcohols are equal. We classify them by the carbon holding the -OH.",
        "keyPoints": [
          "Primary (1°): C-OH is attached to 0 or 1 other Carbon.",
          "Secondary (2°): C-OH is attached to 2 Carbons.",
          "Tertiary (3°): C-OH is attached to 3 Carbons."
        ],
        "examples": [
          "Ethanol: CH3-CH2-OH -> Primary (C has 1 neighbor).",
          "Propan-2-ol: CH3-CH(OH)-CH3 -> Secondary (C has 2 neighbors).",
          "tert-Butyl alcohol: C(CH3)3-OH -> Tertiary (C has 3 neighbors)."
        ],
        "whyItMatters": [
          "This classification predicts how the molecule reacts in oxidation and substitution reactions later."
        ],
        "terminology": [
          "Primary",
          "Secondary",
          "Tertiary"
        ],
        "detailedExplanation": "Look at the carbon atom bonded to the oxygen. Count how many other carbon atoms are directly attached to it.",
        "observedIn": [
          "Reaction mechanisms",
          "Oxidation tests"
        ],
        "visualSupport": [
          "Hand analogy: Palm = C-OH, Fingers = Neighbors."
        ],
        "importantNotes": [
          "Methanol (CH3OH) is a special case; it has no alkyl neighbors but behaves like primary alcohols in many reactions. Treat as Primary for classification purposes."
        ],
        "memoryTechniques": [
          "1° = 1 neighbor, 2° = 2 neighbors, 3° = 3 neighbors (excluding the OH)."
        ],
        "conceptSummary": [
          "Count the carbon neighbors of the C-OH to classify."
        ]
      }
    ],
    "definitions": [
      {
        "term": "Alcohol",
        "definition": "Organic compound with -OH group attached to an sp3 hybridized aliphatic carbon (R-OH)."
      },
      {
        "term": "Phenol",
        "definition": "Compound where a hydroxyl group is directly bonded to an aromatic ring."
      },
      {
        "term": "Primary Alcohol",
        "definition": "Alcohol where the carbon bearing -OH is attached to only one other alkyl group (or none in methanol)."
      }
    ],
    "workedExamples": [
      {
        "title": "Naming and Classifying 2-Methylpropan-1-ol",
        "steps": [
          "Step 1: Identify the longest chain containing OH. It is a 3-carbon chain (Propane).",
          "Step 2: Number from end nearest to OH. C1 has OH.",
          "Step 3: Name parent: Propan-1-ol.",
          "Step 4: Add substituent at position 2: Methyl group -> 2-Methylpropan-1-ol."
        ],
        "explanation": "The longest chain is 3 carbons. The OH is on C1, so it's a primary alcohol because the carbon with OH (C1) is attached to only one other carbon (C2)."
      }
    ],
