  "introduction": "**The Mystery of the -OH Group**\n\n*Teacher Action:* Display two bottles. One labeled 'Ethanol' (clear liquid), one 'Phenol' (white crystals that turn pink in air).\n*Hook Question:* \"Both contain an -OH group. If I put them both in water, which dissolves better? Which is more acidic? Are they the same family of compounds?\n*Inquiry:* Students might guess based on smell or state. Reveal: They are chemically different because one has a ring and the other doesn't. Today we learn how to tell them apart by name and structure!"
  "theory": {
    "overview": "This session introduces the two major classes of oxygenated hydrocarbons in Class XII Chemistry: Alcohols and Phenols. While both contain the hydroxyl (-OH) functional group, their chemical behavior differs significantly due to the nature of the carbon atom they are attached to (aliphatic vs aromatic).",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Alcohols have -OH on sp3 hybridized carbons; Phenols have it on an aromatic ring.",
      "IUPAC naming rules prioritize the longest chain containing OH and use suffix '-ol'.",
      "Classification (1°, 2°, 3°) is based on the number of carbon atoms attached to the C-OH group."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "Alcohols are derivatives of alkanes where a hydrogen atom is replaced by an -OH group. The general formula for mono-hydric saturated alcohols is CnH2n+1OH. Phenols, however, are derivatives of benzene where one hydrogen is replaced by -OH. This structural difference (sp3 vs sp2/aromatic) makes phenols more acidic and less reactive towards nucleophilic substitution compared to alcohols in many contexts.\n\nNomenclature follows strict IUPAC rules: The parent chain must contain the carbon with the OH group. Numbering starts from that end. For example, CH3-CH(OH)-CH2-CH3 is Butan-2-ol (not 1-methylpropan-1-ol). Phenols are named as derivatives of 'phenol' where position 1 is always the carbon with OH.\n\nClassification is crucial for predicting reactivity. A primary alcohol has the C-OH attached to one other carbon (e.g., Ethanol), secondary to two (e.g., Isopropanol), and tertiary to three (e.g., tert-Butyl alcohol). This classification dictates how they undergo oxidation, dehydration, and substitution in subsequent lessons."
  },
